  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Peter 1:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " adds ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "φιλαδελφία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀγάπη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to the virtues already named. These are to be distinguished thus, that the former applies specially to the Christian brethren, the latter to all—without distinction; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 3:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " : ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἡ ἀγάπη εἰς ἀλλήλους καὶ εἰς πάντας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Galatians 6:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "φιλαδελφία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 1:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". While the apostle calls the love which is extended to all ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀγάπη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", he gives it to be understood that what he means is not the purely natural well-wishing, but Christian love springing from the Christian spirit. Dietlein, without sufficient reason, thinks that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "φιλαδελφία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is only the opposite of that which is forbidden in the eighth and ninth commandments, whilst the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀγάπη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is the complete antithesis to what is forbidden in the tenth commandment. In this way the conception ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "φιλαδελφία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is unjustifiably disregarded,—a proceeding to which the language of Scripture gives the less sanction, that where love in all its depth and truth is spoken of, the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "φιλεῖν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is not unfrequently used; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 16:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Although the different virtues here are not arranged according to definite logical order, yet the way in which they here belong to each other is not to be mistaken. Each of the virtues to be shown forth forms the complement of that which precedes, and thus gives rise to a firmly-linked chain of thought. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀρετή",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " supplies the complement of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "πίστις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for faith without virtue is wanting in moral character, and is in itself dead; that of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀρετή",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γνῶσις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for the realizing of the moral volition is conditioned by comprehension of that which is needful in each separate case; that of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "γνῶσις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐγκράτεια",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for self-control must not be wanting to volition and comprehension; that of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐγκράτεια",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
